That text in the corners (URL/file path on the right, date on the left, page numbers at the bottom) isn't from our HTML — it's the browser's default print headers/footers. There are two ways to handle it:

**Option A — User-side fix (no code change):** In the print dialog, expand "More settings" and uncheck "Headers and footers". Reliable but every user has to do it each time.

**Option B — Code-side fix:** Change the CSS so the page has zero margin and we move the spacing inside the body. Most browsers skip rendering default headers/footers when `@page { margin: 0 }` because there's nowhere to put them. Specifically I'd change [templates/index.html:1119](templates/index.html#L1119) and [1134](templates/index.html#L1134) from:

```css
@page { size: letter; margin: 20mm; }
...
@media print { body { padding: 0; } }
```

to:

```css
@page { size: letter; margin: 0; }
...
@media print { body { padding: 20mm; } }
```

The tradeoff for B: it's not 100% guaranteed across browsers (Firefox honors it well, Chrome/Edge usually do, Safari can be inconsistent), and a tech-savvy user can still re-enable headers/footers from the print dialog.

Want me to apply Option B?

